{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1783301881,"nonce":"8oz53KEQGq2q4TSoK8cn0KvKwdY=","title":"MySQL introspection drops `ON UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP` column attributes.","message":"A very common MySQL idiom — `updated_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP ON UPDATE\nCURRENT_TIMESTAMP` — carries the on-update behaviour in `information_schema.COLUMNS.EXTRA`\n(`on update CURRENT_TIMESTAMP`). `crates/squealy-mysql/src/introspect.rs` reads `EXTRA` only for\n`auto_increment` and generated-column detection (`:241-244`), and the neutral `ColumnModel` has no\nfield for an on-update expression, so the attribute is silently dropped on introspection and never\nrendered.\n\nNeeds a model field (e.g. an `on_update` default-like expression on the column, MySQL-specific /\n`Raw`-carried) plus read + render. Round-tripping a table with `ON UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP`\ncurrently loses it.\n\nFound in the introspection round-trip audit (see ~/.claude/plans/squealy-introspection-audit.md).","files":null}]}